text:
11th Street, east side, north from Borden Avenue. The block to 51st Avenue is used as a dump, across which is a two-story frame house, no. 11-11 51st Avenue. Across the block from Borden to 51st Avenues, running in a northeasterly direction, was later constructed part of the highway leading to the entrance of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 11, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

folder: 11th Street & North Borden Avenue., Queens, NY
text:
11th Street (left), east side, north from Borden Avenue to 51st Avenue, showing this area before it was converted into the plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. The broad approach to the tunnel was laid out across this area in a northeasterly direction toward the Queens Borough Hall, seen in the right background.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

folder: 11th Street & North Borden Avenue., Queens, NY
text:
11th Street, west side, north from Borden to 51st Avenues. The tenements, the rears of which are seen, front on the south side of 51st Avenue and are Nos. 10-54 to 10-40. This whole area, after the buildings were razed, was reconstructed into the plaza of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel; the tunnel's toll booths were erected here.

November 17, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

Borden Avenue, east from 11th Street. On the north side of the avenue, at 21st Street, are several factories, the first one being the Mavis Building. Viewing northeastward across the clearance and wooden fence, is the line of the elevated highway which will be built here to carry traffic to and from the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. In the center background is the Queens Borough Hall.

November 18, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

Borden Avenue, south side, east from 11th Street, showing the Long Island Railroad yards in the immediate vicinity of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.

November 18, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

Borden Avenue, north side, west from 11th Street to Vernon Boulevard. All the structures seen in this view were later town down and upon the site was constructed the Queens-Midtown Tunnel plaza. The area in the front, where the fence stretches to the right, marks the exact location where the toll booths were erected. In the right background is the spire of St. Mary's Roman Catholic Church. November 21, 1938. New York City Tunnel Authority.

Borden Avenue, north side, west from 11th Street, toward the vehicular viaduct on Vernon Boulevard. All the structures seen in this view, some of them (right) fronting on the south side of 51st Avenue, were later torn down to make way for the construction of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel plaza. The tall building is the Clay Building, on Jackson Avenue.

November 17, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

Borden Avenue, south side, west from 11th Street to the Vernon Boulevard vehicular viaduct, showing the Long Island Railroad yards in the immediate vicinity of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel plaza.

November 17, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

Borden Avenue, north side, east from 11th to 21st Streets. The general view is in a northeasterly direction across the dumps, which marks the line of the elevated concrete highway which was later thrown across here leading from the exit of the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. On the right is the Mavis Building and a Long Island RR water tower. In the center background is the Queens Borough Hall, 21st Street and 49th Avenue.

November 11, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority
